         My mistake Xzzy, I had not realized that DAoC had jumped up quite that quickly.</P><P>I would be interested in knowing how many of those 200K still had active EQ accounts when they started DAoC. If you were to factor out the people that still played on both platforms, I wonder what portion of the online market DAoC acctually commanded.</P><P>To answer to your question Fazzeel. Because I know better now. </P><P>When I first started EQ, it was my first online gaming experience. I did not know any better. Hell, at the time, no one knew any better, as back then, there was not much of a high-end game. Just a scads of people trying to figure shit out, with the occasional uber guild that could actually /gasp take down Trakanon. Fungi Tunics were the stuff of legend. Froglock Bonecaster Robes gave most players wet dreams. </P><P>Watching it all unfold has told me a different story. I enjoyed my time in EQ, no questions, but I despise Verant and their seeming illogical actions. In real life, if I buy a car that falls apart on me, guess what, when I buy my next car, it will NEVER be from that manufacturer again. With EQ, yes, Verant did manage to hook me for a long time. But, having the knowledge of Verant will allow me to make an informed decision about the next gaming platform I join.</P><P>Why will I not chose another Verant game? Again, because I know better this time around. They can take their pathetic excuse for customer service, their under-tested products and their seeming total lack of listening to customer feedback and shove it straight up their collective asses. </P><P>Cheers,<BR><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=63522">Ancagalon the Black </a><BR>Warlock - Terris Thule</P><P><BR>Edited by - Ancagalon on 10/02/2002  16:16:02<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
